[[lt:Pasaulio šalių didmiesčiai]]

The '''lowest bridging point''' is the location on a river which is crossed by a bridge at its closest point to the sea.<ref>[http://geographyfieldwork.com/urban_geography_glossary.htm Barcelona Field Studies Centre: Urban Geography Glossary]. Retrieved 24 February 2014</ref>
Historically - that is, before the development of engineering technology that allowed the construction of tunnels and high-level road bridges - the lowest bridging point of a river was frequently the point at which an important town or city grew up, and particularly where trade and commerce took place. The place could be served by roads on either side of the river, allowing access from a wide [[hinterland]]; had river transport available upstream; and often was at a location that allowed seagoing traffic to approach it from a downstream direction.
Examples of lowest bridging points in Britain include [[London]], the lowest bridging point on the [[Thames]];<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=RKuWgcPPUJIC&pg=PA42&dq=%22lowest+bridging+point%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=g6kLU7-uG8P17AappICgBA&ved=0CDUQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=%22lowest%20bridging%20point%22&f=false Neil Anthony Punnett, ''The New Wider World'', Nelson Thornes, 2003, p.42]</ref> [[Lancaster, Lancashire|Lancaster]], the lowest bridging point on the [[River Lune|Lune]];<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=Xm4KAQAAMAAJ&q=%22lowest+bridging+point%22&dq=%22lowest+bridging+point%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=g6kLU7-uG8P17AappICgBA&ved=0CFYQ6AEwBw Andrew White, ''Lancaster: a history'', Phillimore, 2003, p.125]</ref> [[York]], the lowest bridging point on the [[River Ouse, Yorkshire|Ouse]];<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=SnNmAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT46&dq=%22lowest+bridging+point%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=ZaoLU7jPIOPd7QaC9YHAAw&ved=0CC4Q6AEwADgK#v=onepage&q=%22lowest%20bridging%20point%22&f=false D. M. Palliser, ''Medieval York: 600-1540'', Oxford University Press, 2014, p.7]</ref> and [[Gloucester]], the lowest bridging point on the [[Severn]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=YLM8AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA150&dq=%22lowest+bridging+point%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=ZaoLU7jPIOPd7QaC9YHAAw&ved=0CEkQ6AEwBTgK#v=onepage&q=%22lowest%20bridging%20point%22&f=false A. F. Martin, "The Upper Thames basin", in Jean B. Mitchell (ed.), ''Great Britain: Geographical Essays'', Cambridge University Press, 1962, p.150]</ref> [[Glasgow]] grew up at the lowest bridging point on the [[River Clyde|Clyde]] which was about twelve miles upstream from its lowest fording point at [[Milton_Island#Dumbuck_Ford|Dumbuck]]. [[Mathew Paris]]’s map of 1247 appears to show only one bridge in the whole of Britain: at [[Stirling]], the lowest bridging point on the [[River Forth]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Stirling Old Bridge|url=http://scotlandsoldestbridges.co.uk/stirling-old-bridge.html|website=Scotland's Oldest Bridges|publisher=The catalogue contains 525 bridges|accessdate=7 April 2017}}</ref>
